      "content": "I sometimes get carried away with my analogies. I'll keep the math-focused explanation going.\n\nThink of the p-value like a threshold for a goblin's treasure map. The null hypothesis is like the map, and the p-value is the probability that the goblin (or in this case, the observed results) would stumble upon the treasure (or significant difference in blood pressure) by chance. A p-value of 0.04 means that if the null hypothesis is true (the drug has no effect), there's only a 4% chance that the observed results would occur. This doesn't imply that the null hypothesis is false, but rather that the results are statistically significant, indicating that the observed difference might be real.",
